	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The way I understand it:
<br />
<br />Sprite DMA ($4014) is nothing more than a CPU macro which auto-fetches bytes and feeds them to $2004.  So what happens if DMA "spills" into rendering is the same as what would happen if you wrote to $2004 during rendering (because that's pretty much exactly what's happening).
<br />
<br />From what I understand -- $2004 writes during rendering have no effect (they may or may not increment $2003 -- I'd really like clarification on this). 
<br />
<br />Meaning if you DMA with only 101 CPU cycles left in VBlank -- only 50 bytes will have been successfully copied to OAM (and possibly $2003 will only += 50?  again confirmation welcome), the other 413 cycles that the DMA "eats" will still be wasted, but will have no effect.
<br />
<br />
<br />Of course if the PPU is off, DMA/$2004 can be done any time without any trouble.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
